          "body": "2 Kings 9 opens with an act of prophetic delegation: Elisha sends an unnamed 'son of the prophets' to anoint Jehu king in secret (9:1-3). The commission to anoint Jehu was originally given to Elijah at Horeb (1 Kings 19:16) but was never personally executed by him — Elisha now carries it to completion. The urgency of the anointing scene is palpable: the messenger is told to pour the oil, speak the word, open the door, and flee without delay (9:3). There is something almost combustible about the commission — once delivered, it cannot be contained. The word of the LORD spoken in a private room at Ramoth-gilead sets an entire dynasty on a collision course with judgment. The rest of the chapter is simply the working out of what that oil and that word put into motion."
