          "title": "Shalom's impossible condition",
          "body": "The word *shalom* — peace, wholeness, wellbeing — is repeated six times across verses 11-31, and each time it is either a question or a denial. Joram's messengers ask Jehu whether he comes in peace; Jehu dismisses them and conscripts them. Joram asks personally; Jehu declares that shalom is impossible while Jezebel's harlotries and witchcrafts persist (9:22). Jezebel asks it sarcastically from the window (9:31). The chapter's repeated interrogation of shalom is not incidental. It surfaces the chapter's theological diagnosis: the absence of shalom in Israel is not a political problem but a spiritual one. A kingdom whose queen-mother practices *zanun* (sexual/spiritual unfaithfulness — idolatry cast in marital imagery) and *kesheph* (witchcraft, occult manipulation) cannot have shalom with a God who is light and in whom there is no darkness (cf. 1 John 1:5). Jehu's repeated refusal to answer 'yes' to the shalom question is the chapter's most sustained theological statement."
