          "title": "Naboth's field — the land that remembered",
          "body": "The most theologically freighted moment in the chapter is the encounter at 'the property of Naboth the Jezreelite' (9:21). The narrator's geographical precision is deliberate: out of all the ground in Jezreel, Joram's chariot meets Jehu exactly there. When Jehu orders Bidkar to cast Joram's body on that same field (9:25), he cites the oracle spoken by the LORD when he and Bidkar were riding together behind Ahab — likely the very day of 1 Kings 21:17-19. The LORD is quoted directly (9:26): 'Surely I have seen yesterday the blood of Naboth and the blood of his sons.' The adverb 'yesterday' (*emesh*) is theologically arresting: the blood is still fresh before God. Divine justice does not operate on a statute of limitations. The land to which Ahab had no legal or moral claim becomes the land on which his son's body is cast and on which Elijah's oracle is finally satisfied. The field is not just a location; it is a theological exhibit."
