          "body": "Jezebel's final scene (9:30-37) is the chapter's most dramatically intense. She does not flee or negotiate; she adorns herself and looks out the window — the posture of royal contempt and perhaps calculated seduction. Her taunt — 'Is it well, Zimri, your master's murderer?' (9:31) — invokes the precedent of Zimri, whose coup against Baasha's son lasted exactly seven days (1 Kings 16:15-20). The taunt is designed to frame Jehu as a usurper who will meet the same fate. Instead, Jehu calls for her own household servants, and it is her own eunuchs who throw her down (9:33). The detail that she is trampled by the horses and that when they return to bury her they find only 'the skull and the feet and the palms of her hands' (9:35) fulfills the oracle with a specificity that staggers: 'In the property of Jezreel the dogs shall eat the flesh of Jezebel' (9:36). The narrator's commentary — 'and the corpse of Jezebel will be as dung on the face of the field in the property of Jezreel, so they cannot say, this is Jezebel' (9:37) — is not gratuitous. The woman who spent her life accumulating identity, power, and royal prestige is denied in death even the dignity of a name on a grave."
