        "excerpt": "When Ahaziah the king of Judah saw this, he fled by the way of the garden house.",
        "body": "The death of Ahaziah king of Judah is narrated with notable compression — three verses compared to the extended scenes for Joram and Jezebel. This compression is itself theologically significant: Ahaziah is not the primary target of the commission (the house of Ahab is), but he is caught in the judgment's sweep because he is Ahab's dynasty by blood. His mother was Athaliah, daughter of Ahab and Jezebel (2 Kings 8:26), which means Ahaziah was both the reigning king of Judah and the biological grandson of Ahab. He had come to Jezreel to visit his ailing uncle Joram (9:16) — an act of family solidarity that placed him in the path of YHWH's judgment.\n\nThe chronicler's parallel account in 2 Chronicles 22:7-9 provides additional detail and frames Ahaziah's death as part of his appointed judgment rather than an accident of proximity. The question of whether Jehu exceeded his mandate in killing a Davidic king has exercised commentators. The commission in verses 7-10 names the 'house of Ahab' as the target, and Ahaziah's Judahite throne made him technically outside that designation. Yet his maternal lineage and his active association with Joram placed him squarely within the Omride network. Hosea 1:4, written later, will pronounce YHWH's judgment on 'the house of Jehu' for 'the bloodshed of Jezreel' — a text that most commentators take as a retrospective divine assessment that Jehu ultimately exceeded the limits of his commission, even while the commission itself was genuine.\n\nThe burial note in verse 28 — Ahaziah's servants carrying him to Jerusalem for burial 'in his tomb with his fathers in the city of David' — provides a deliberate contrast with what follows for Jezebel. A Davidic king, however compromised, receives honorable burial in the royal cemetery. The distinction the narrator draws between Ahaziah's burial and Jezebel's non-burial is not accidental; it reflects the enduring covenant significance of the Davidic line even in its worst moments.\n\nThe chronological synchronism of verse 29 — 'in the eleventh year of Joram the son of Ahab, Ahaziah became king over Judah' — is one of several regnal synchronisms in Kings that have exercised text-critical scholars (compare 2 Kings 8:25, which gives 'the twelfth year'). The difference is likely a matter of whether accession-year or non-accession-year reckoning is applied. The narrator's purpose in inserting it here is to anchor Ahaziah's death within the annalistic structure of regnal history, locating the event precisely in Israel's covenantal timeline."
